{{Software-stub}}

[[File:Tower of London - 01.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The Tower of London seen from the Thames]] The '''Lieutenant of the Tower of London''' served directly under the [[Constable of the Tower]]. The office was appointed at least since the 13th century. There were formerly many privileges, immunities and perquisites attached to the office. Like the Constable, the [[Lieutenant]] was usually appointed by [[letters patent]], either for life or during the King's pleasure.{{sfn|Bayley|1825|p=664}}
The Lieutenants had custody of many eminent prisoners of state, including [[Anne Boleyn]], [[Sir Thomas More]], [[Lady Jane Grey]], [[Elizabeth I of England|Princess Elizabeth]] (later Queen Elizabeth I) and [[Sir Walter Raleigh]]. At least five of the Lieutenants, Sir [[Edward Warner (1511–1565)|Edward Warner]],{{sfn|Croly|2004}} Sir [[Gervase Helwys]],{{sfn|Bellany|2004}} [[Isaac Penington (Lord Mayor)|Isaac Penington]],{{sfn|Lindley|2004}} [[Robert Tichborne|Colonel Robert Tichborne]],{{sfn|Lindley 27430|2004}} and [[Sir Edward Hales, 3rd Baronet|Sir Edward Hales]],{{sfn|Hopkins|2004}} themselves later became prisoners in the Tower.
==History==
===Edward I to Henry VIII=== The earliest known Lieutenant was [[Giles de Oudenard]] at the beginning of the reign of [[Edward I of England|Edward I]], while [[Antony Bek (bishop of Durham)|Anthony Bek]], later [[Bishop of Durham]], was Constable. The next Lieutenant of whom there is record was [[Ralph Bavant]], who served during [[Barons Cromwell|John de Crumwell's]] tenure as Constable.{{sfn|Bayley|1825|p=665}}
In the reign of [[Henry V of England|Henry V]], Sir Roger Aston served as Lieutenant under William, Lord Bourchier, who was then Constable. Among their notable prisoners was [[James I of Scotland]].{{sfn|Bayley|1825|p=665}} Sir Robert Scott served as Lieutenant in 1424 during the reign of [[Henry VI of England|Henry VI]].{{sfn|Fleming|2008}} During the reign of [[Edward IV of England|Edward IV]], Richard Haute (died 8 April 1487) was Lieutenant from 1471 to 1473.{{sfn|Fleming|2004}}{{sfn|Richardson II|2011|p=597}} [[John de Vere, 13th Earl of Oxford]] was Constable in the reign of [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]], at which time Sir John Digby was his Lieutenant.{{sfn|Bayley|1825|p=665}}
[[Image:St-Peter-Ad-Vincula.jpg|thumb|right|[[St. Peter ad Vincula (London)|St. Peter ad Vincula]], a chapel on [[Tower Green]], is the resting place of several of the Lieutenants of the Tower.]] According to some sources, in the reign of [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]] Sir [[Thomas Lovell]] (died 25 May 1524) served as Lieutenant from [[Michaelmas]] 1512;{{sfn|Gunn|2004}} however according to other sources, he was Constable of the Tower.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/lovell-sir-thomas-i-1450-1524 |chapter=Lovell, Sir Thomas I (by 1450-1524), of East Harling, Norfolk, and Elsing by Enfield, Middlesex |title=History of Parliament |accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref> Among the prisoners of state in Lovell's custody was the Pretender to the Crown, [[Lambert Simnel]].{{sfn|Gunn|2004}} The Lieutenant from 1513 to 1520 was Sir [[Richard Cholmondeley]] (died 1521).{{sfn|Baker|2004}} Cholmondeley held office during the [[Evil May Day]] riots of 1517. During the riots, he furiously ordered the firing of some of the Tower's artillery at the city during rioting by gangs of young Londoners, who took control of London for several days, drawing the ire of the city elders. In 1520, he resigned his post at the Tower due to ill health. He died in March 1521 (1522 by the modern calendar system) in [[St Katharine's by the Tower]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Chamley |first=Benson |date=June 2003 |title=Sir Richard Cholmondeley, Cheshire's most famous unknown |journal=The Family History Society of Cheshire Magazine}}</ref>
Cholmondeley was succeeded by Sir [[Edmund Walsingham]],{{sfn|Robison|2004}} Sir William Sidney, Sir [[Anthony Knyvett (1507–1554)|Anthony Knyvet]], and Sir [[Walter Stonor]].{{sfn|Bayley|1825|p=665}} Walsingham had personal charge of a number of eminent prisoners of state during his tenure, among them the [[Margaret Pole, Countess of Salisbury|Countess of Salisbury]], [[Arthur Plantagenet, 1st Viscount Lisle|Viscount Lisle]], [[Anne Boleyn]], [[John Fisher|Bishop John Fisher]] and Sir [[Thomas More]].{{sfn|Robison|2004}}<ref name=history>{{cite web |url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/walsingham-sir-edmund-1480-1550 |chapter=Walsingham, Sir Edmund (by 1480-1550), of Scadbury, Chislehurst, Kent |title=History of Parliament |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> Leonard Skeffington, son of Sir [[William Skeffington]] (died 31 December 1535) is also said to have served as Lieutenant during the reign of Henry VIII and to have invented an instrument of torture used in the Tower; however there appears to be no record of his appointment or tenure as Lieutenant.{{sfn|Lyons|2004}}
===Edward VI to Charles I=== During the reign of [[Edward VI of England|Edward VI]], Sir [[John Markham (Died 1559)|John Markham]] was appointed Lieutenant in 1549 but dismissed on 31 October 1551 for leniency towards his prisoners, including the [[Edward Seymour, 1st Duke of Somerset|Protector Somerset]] and Sir [[Michael Stanhope (died 1552)|Michael Stanhope]].{{sfn|Cameron|2004}} Sir [[Arthur Darcy]] also served briefly as Lieutenant during Edward VI's reign.{{sfn|Leedham-Green|2004}}{{sfn|Bayley|1825|p=665}} Sir [[Edward Warner (1511–1565)|Edward Warner]] was appointed Lieutenant in October 1552.{{sfn|Croly|2004}}
During the crisis after the death of Edward VI, Warner held the Tower of London for [[John Dudley, 1st Duke of Northumberland]], and was immediately removed from his post on [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary's]] accession. In 1554 he was a prisoner in the Tower, but was pardoned in 1555.{{sfn|Croly|2004}}<ref name=Warner>{{cite web |url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/warner-sir-edward-1511-65 |chapter=Warner, Sir Edward (1511-65), of Polsteadhall and Plumstead, Norfolk |title=History of Parliament |accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref> Queen Mary appointed [[John Brydges, 1st Baron Chandos]] as Lieutenant from August 1553 to June 1554. He is said to have 'rigorously' shaken the rebel [[Thomas Wyatt the Younger|Thomas Wyatt]] when he was brought to the Tower, and to have called him a "villain and unhappy traitor".{{citation needed|date=March 2014}} He had custody of [[Lady Jane Grey]], who gave him her prayer book as a memento when she was executed, and of the future [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth]], whom he was considered to have treated too leniently.{{sfn|Norris|2004}} He was succeeded by his brother, Sir [[Thomas Bridges (MP)|Thomas Bridges]] (died 1559).{{sfn|Bayley|1825|p=665}}<ref>However, according to Ashley, Thomas Brydges was deputy under his brother, Sir John Brydges {{harv|Ashley|2004}}</ref> Sir [[Henry Bedingfeld|Henry Bedingfield]] was appointed in October 1555 and served until the end of 1556.{{sfn|Weikel|2004}} He was succeeded by Sir [[Robert Oxenbridge (1508-1574)|Robert Oxenbridge]], who was appointed Lieutenant in 1556, and was Constable in 1557.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/oxenbridge-sir-robert-15089-74 |chapter=Oxenbridge, Sir Robert (1508/9-74), of Brede, Sussex, and Hurstbourne Priors, Hampshire |title=History of Parliament |accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref>{{sfn|Bayley|1825|p=665}}
When [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]] acceded to the throne in November 1558, she reappointed Sir Edward Warner as Lieutenant{{sfn|Croly|2004}} jointly with Sir [[Thomas Cawarden]].{{sfn|Robison|2008}}<ref name=Warner/> They served together for less than a month, from 17 November to 10 December 1558, and Cawarden died shortly thereafter in August 1559.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/cawarden-thomas-1514-59 |chapter=Cawarden, Thomas (by 1514-59), of Blackfriars, London and Bletchingley, Surrey |title=History of Parliament |accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref> Warner's most notable prisoner was [[Lady Catherine Grey|Lady Katherine Grey]], who had incurred the Queen's wrath by secretly marrying [[Edward Seymour, 1st Earl of Hertford]]. Warner was dismissed about 1561 for excessive leniency,{{sfn|Croly|2004}}<ref name=Warner/> and was succeeded by Sir Richard Blount, after whose sudden death Sir [[Francis Jobson]] was appointed on 20 August 1564. Jobson was Lieutenant during the [[Northern Rising]], and according to Narsingha held office until his own death on 4 June 1573.{{sfn|Narasingha|2004}} However according to other sources Sir [[Owen Hopton]] was appointed Lieutenant in 1570.<ref name=Hopton>{{cite web |url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1558-1603/member/hopton-owen-1519-95 |chapter=Hopton, Owen (c.1519-95), of Yoxford and Blythburgh, Suffolk and of London |title=History of Parliament |accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref> Among his prisoners were [[Henry Wriothesley, 2nd Earl of Southampton]], [[Thomas Howard, 4th Duke of Norfolk]], and Norfolk's son and heir, [[Philip Howard, 20th Earl of Arundel|Philip Howard, Earl of Arundel]].{{sfn|Craig|2004}} Financial difficulties occasioned Hopton's resignation in the summer of 1590.<ref name=Hopton/> Hopton was followed in office by Sir [[Michael Blount]],{{sfn|Baker|2008}} Sir [[Richard Berkeley (died 1604)|Richard Berkeley]] (appointed in 1596){{sfn|Strachan|2004}} and Sir [[Drue Drury (courtier)|Drue Drury]], who was appointed in November 1595, but resigned due to ill health in September 1596.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1558-1603/member/drury-dru-1527-1617 |chapter=Drury, Dru (aft.1527-1617), of Riddlesworth, Norfolk |title=History of Parliament |accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref>{{sfn|Lowe|2004}} Sir John Peyton was appointed Lieutenant in June 1597, and as Lieutenant was present at the execution in 1601 of [[Robert Devereux, 2nd Earl of Essex]]. Another of Peyton's eminent prisoners was Sir [[Walter Raleigh]]. On 30 July 1603, shortly after the accession of [[James VI and I|James I]], Peyton was relieved of his post, and appointed [[Governor of Jersey]].{{sfn|Evans|2004}}{{sfn|Bayley|1825|pp=665-6}}
[[File:Sir William Wadd late Lieutenant of the Tower.png|left|thumb|upright|Sir William Wadd, engraving after an original portrait]] Sir George Harvey (died 10 August 1605) was the first Lieutenant of the Tower under King James.{{sfn|Bayley|1825|p=666}} He was succeeded by Sir [[William Wade (English politician)|William Waad]], who was Lieutenant during the [[Gunpowder plot]]. Waad retired from public life in 1613, and was succeeded in the office by Sir [[Gervase Helwys]], who was appointed on 6 May 1613. During Helwys' tenure as Lieutenant, his prisoner, Sir [[Thomas Overbury]], was poisoned, and on 20 November 1615 Helwys was hanged on [[Tower Hill]] for the murder.{{sfn|Bellany|2004}} In October 1615, Sir [[George More]] was appointed Lieutenant 'to keep close watch over [[Robert Carr, 1st Earl of Somerset|Robert]] and [[Frances Carr, Countess of Somerset|Frances Carr]], earl and countess of Somerset, over the poisoning of Sir Thomas Overbury'.{{sfn|Knafla|2004}} In January 1617 More was said to be ‘weary of that troublesome and dangerous office’, and sold it, in March of that year, to Sir [[Allen Apsley (administrator)|Allan Apsley]] for £2500.{{sfn|Knafla|2004}}{{sfn|Round|2004}}{{sfn|Bayley|1825|p=666}} Sir [[Thomas Warner (explorer)|Thomas Warner]] also served as Lieutenant by appointment of James I at some time before embarking on colonial ventures in April 1620.{{sfn|LaCombe|2004}}
Apsley continued to serve as Lieutenant under [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] until his death. He was succeeded on 18 October 1630 by Sir [[William Balfour (general)|William Balfour]]. Balfour resigned the office on 22 December 1641,{{sfn|Furgol|2004}} and on 22 December the King appointed Sir [[Thomas Lunsford]] as Lieutenant, sparking opposition from the House of Commons which forced the King to replace Lunsford with Sir [[John Byron, 1st Baron Byron|John Byron]] on 26 December.{{sfn|Morgan|2004}} Byron resigned on 11 February 1642, again as a result of pressure from the Commons,{{sfn|Hutton|2004}} and was replaced by [[Conyers baronets|Sir John Conyers]], who served until 11 August 1643, when he surrendered the office to Sir [[Robert Harley (1579–1656)|Robert Harley]].{{sfn|Hopper|2004}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=37318 |title=House of Lords Journal Volume 6: 11 August 1643 |pages=177–178 |accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref> The London alderman and [[List of Lord Mayors of London|Lord Mayor]] [[Isaac Penington (Lord Mayor)|Isaac Penington]] is said to have been appointed Lieutenant in July 1643, and as Lieutenant to have accompanied [[William Laud|Archbishop Laud]] to his beheading on [[Tower Hill]] in 1645. Penington spent the last years of his life as a prisoner in the Tower, and died there on 16 December 1661.{{sfn|Lindley|2004}}{{sfn|Bayley|1825|p=666}} He was succeeded in the Lieutenancy by Francis West (died 11 August 1652).{{sfn|Lindley 29081|2004}}
===Cromwell and later=== [[Image:Colonel John Barkstead regicide.jpg|right|thumb|150px|John Barkstead]] Under the Protector [[Oliver Cromwell]], [[John Barkstead]] was appointed to the Lieutenancy in August 1652, and held the office until 1659.{{sfn|Durston|2004}} In August 1647 [[Robert Tichborne|Colonel Robert Tichborne]] was appointed Lieutenant.{{sfn|Lindley 27430|2004}} Both Barkstead and Tichborne were [[regicide]]s, and Tichborne died a prisoner in the Tower after the Restoration.{{sfn|Lindley 27430|2004}} They were followed in the office by Colonel Thomas Fitch and Colonel [[Herbert Morley]] (appointed 7 January 1660).{{sfn|Peacey|2004}}{{sfn|Bayley|1825|p=666}}
After the [[Restoration (England)|Restoration]] of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]], Morley was replaced by [[Sir John Robinson, 1st Baronet, of London|Sir John Robinson]], who was appointed Lieutenant in June 1660 and continued in the office until May 1679, when the King dismissed him as a result of pressure from the Commons.{{sfn|Seaward|2004}}{{sfn|Bayley|1825|p=666}}
Among those appointed in subsequent reigns were [[Thomas Cheke]], esquire, [[Sir Edward Hales, 3rd Baronet|Sir Edward Hales]] (who was appointed 13 June 1687, and was himself a prisoner in the Tower with his brother, Charles, in January 1689){{sfn|Hopkins|2004}} and Sir [[Bevil Skelton]] during the reign of [[James II of England|James II]]; [[John Farewell]], during the reign of [[William I of England|William I]]; [[Charles Churchill (British Army general)|Charles Churchill]] (appointed in 1702, resigned in 1706),{{sfn|Snell|2004}} and [[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-General]] [[William Cadogan, 1st Earl Cadogan|William Cadogan]], (1709–1712), during the reign of [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Queen Anne]], and Lieutenant-General Sir [[Hatton Compton]],{{sfn|Haydon|2004}} Lieutenant-General Vernon, and General Loftus.{{sfn|Bayley|1825|p=666}}
==Holders of the office since 1700== {{columns-list|colwidth=30em| * 1702: [[Charles Churchill (British Army general)|Charles Churchill]] * 1706: ''vacant'' * 1709: [[William Cadogan, 1st Earl Cadogan|William Cadogan]] * 1713: [[Hatton Compton]] * 1742: [[Harry Powlett, 4th Duke of Bolton|Lord Harry Powlett]]<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=8131|page=2|date=26–29 June 1742}}</ref> * 1754: [[Charles Powlett, 5th Duke of Bolton|The Duke of Bolton]] * 1760: [[George Paulet, 12th Marquess of Winchester|George Powlett]]<ref>{{London Gazette|nolink=y|issue=10011|page=1|date=21–24 June 1760}}</ref> * 1763: [[Charles Vernon (1719–1810)|Charles Vernon]]<ref>{{London Gazette|nolink=y|issue=10344|page=1|date=30 August–3 September 1763}}</ref> * 1810: [[William Loftus (British Army officer)|William Loftus]]<ref>{{London Gazette|nolink=y|issue=16396|page=1223|date=14–18 August 1810}}</ref> * 1831: [[George FitzClarence, 1st Earl of Munster|The Earl of Munster]]<ref>{{London Gazette|nolink=y|issue=18827|page=1478|date=22 July 1831}}</ref> * 1833: [[Lord Frederick FitzClarence]]<ref>{{London Gazette|nolink=y|issue=19015|page=146|date=22 January 1833}}</ref> * 1833: [[John Sulivan Wood]]<ref>{{London Gazette|nolink=y|issue=19025|page=399|date=26 February 1833}}</ref> * 16 July 1851: Sir [[George Bowles (British Army officer)|George Bowles]]<ref>{{London Gazette|nolink=y|issue=21228|page=1857|date=18 July 1851}}</ref> * 22 July 1876: [[Charles Lennox Brownlow Maitland]]<ref>{{London Gazette|nolink=y|issue=24348|page=4178|date=25 July 1876}}</ref> * 4 June 1884: [[Frederic Thesiger, 2nd Baron Chelmsford|The Lord Chelmsford]]<ref>{{London Gazette|nolink=y|issue=25361|page=2439|date=3 June 1884}}</ref> * 30 March 1889: Sir [[George Wentworth Alexander Higginson]] * 21 June 1893: [[Hugh Rowlands]]<ref>{{London Gazette|nolink=y|issue=26417|page=3712|date=30 June 1893}}</ref> * 5 January 1894: [[John Hart Dunne]]<ref>{{London Gazette|nolink=y|issue=26482|page=764|date=6 February 1894}}</ref> *