[[Image:Entrance to Ticho house, Jerusalem.jpg|thumb|250px|Ticho House]]
[[File:Jerusalem Ticho House Entrance.jpg|thumb|250px|Ticho House Entrance]]
'''Ticho House''' ({{lang-he|בית טיכו}}, ''Beit Tikho'') is a historical home in [[Jerusalem]], [[Israel]], now functioning as a [[museum]], administered as part of the national [[Israel Museum]], which includes a restaurant and cultural center. It was one of the first homes built outside the [[Old City (Jerusalem)|Old City walls]] during the 1860s. {{cn|date=August 2014}}

==History==
The house was constructed by a wealthy Arab, Aga Rashid [[Nashashibi]], in 1864.{{cn|date=May 2015}} Antiquities dealer [[Moses Shapira|Moses Wilhelm Shapira]] lived in the house with his family between 1873 and 1883.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://members.bib-arch.org/publication.asp?PubID=BSAO&Volume=5&Issue=5&ArticleID=9 |title=Fakes! |author=Hershel Shanks |work=Archaeology Odyssey 5:05, Sep/Oct 2002 |publisher=Biblical Archaeology Society |year=2002 |accessdate=2014-12-06 }}</ref> In 1924, Dr. Abraham Albert Ticho, an ophthalmologist, and his wife, [[Anna Ticho]], an artist, bought the house.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/news/features/peeking-through-the-highrises-famed-jerusalem-street-s-old-architectural-glories.premium-1.461294 Peeking through the highrises: famed Jerusalem street's old architectural glories, [[Haaretz]]]</ref> Dr. Ticho was stabbed and seriously wounded during the [[1929 Palestine riots]] outside his eye clinic near [[Damascus Gate]].<ref>[http://travel.nytimes.com/travel/guides/middle-east/israel/jerusalem/attraction-detail.html?vid=1154654611891 Beit Ticho - Reviews and Ratings of Sights in Jerusalem - New York Times Travel<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071029022829/http://travel.nytimes.com/travel/guides/middle-east/israel/jerusalem/attraction-detail.html?vid=1154654611891 |date=2007-10-29 }}</ref> After his recovery, Dr. Ticho used the first floor as his new clinic, from where served the population of Jerusalem until his death in 1960.<ref>[http://www.english.imjnet.org.il/htmls/page_1712.aspx?c0=15183&bsp=14296 Ticho House - Israel Museum] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120141726/http://www.english.imjnet.org.il/htmls/page_1712.aspx?c0=15183&bsp=14296 |date=2012-01-20 }}</ref> Anna Ticho hosted local and British government officials in her home, as well as many artists, writers, academics and intellectuals. 

Anna Ticho bequeathed the house and all its contents, including her husband's [[Judaica]] collections and library, to the city of Jerusalem.{{cn|date=August 2014}}

==Anna==
Ticho House operates the kosher dairy restaurant, Anna Italian Café, operating in part of the first floor and the garden. Live jazz and classical music performances are also held there.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/travel-in-israel/ticho-house-1.242511 Ticho House gallery and restaurant]</ref>

